              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Kaldor-Hicks efficiency?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-15-3.jpg" alt="What is the Kaldor-Hicks efficiency?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Kaldor-Hicks efficiency is an economic idea that looks at whether a change in resource use can improve overall societal welfare, even if some people lose out. It was introduced by Nicholas Kaldor and John Hicks in the 1930s. Unlike Pareto Efficiency, which requires everyone to benefit without anyone being worse off, Kaldor-Hicks allows for some losses as long as the overall gains are greater.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">For example, imagine building a highway that displaces a few families but boosts the local economy by creating jobs and reducing travel time for thousands of people. Even though the displaced families lose out, the project could be considered Kaldor-Hicks efficient because the total benefits to society outweigh the costs.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">This concept is often used in cost-benefit analysis for policymaking and investments to decide if a project increases overall economic welfare. However, it‚Äôs criticized for not ensuring fairness or compensating those negatively affected by the change.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
